<TITLE> Taiwan simulates China attack amid hopes for better ties </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TAIPEI, April 22 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Taiwan launched military exercises simulating an attack by rival China on Tuesday, even as President-elect Ma Ying-jeou pushes for improved ties with Beijing in hopes of boosting the island's economy. In the scenario for the Yushan exercise, held each year, it is 2020 and China has launched an all-out attack on Taiwan's east coast using its first aircraft carrier, according to the National Security Council. The annual exercise will run until Sunday in three stages. China has claimed self-ruled Taiwan as its territory since the end of the Chinese civil war in 1949 and pledged to bring the island under its rule, by force if necessary. Despite tense political relations under the administration of outgoing President Chen Shui-bian, whose Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) favours formal independence from China, trade relations have flourished. Taiwan businesses have invested up to $100 billion in China in the last 20 years, and the mainland is now Taiwan's biggest trading partner. Many hope political relations will thaw under Ma, whose platform of improving the economy in part through better ties with Beijing helped propel him to an overwhelming victory in Marc
